author: @1truefreedomfighter
text: Great tutorials!! I'll plan to visit your patreon soon.  The shell interprets the "*" and enumerates all filenames in the current directory in its place. Type "echo *" to see exactly what it does.  Tip: Use echo to view commands containing the "*". (eg: "echo git add *") Notice "ls *" in this example will give the same output as "ls modified.txt my_dir new_file.txt"  Since the * will not pickup files that don't exist, it doesn't add your deleted file. Since the * added the dirname, you got the deleted tracked files in "git add -A my_dir".  ref: http://www.grymoire.com/Unix/Sh.html

author: @virgo47
text: Great tutorial series. If you want to see what is passed when * is used, don't use "ls *", but rather "echo *" - that does not expand/interpret anything in any way, just prints what bash/shell gives you for *. So yes, it added two files and one dir just as you assumed. Funny thing about * is that you can just write it alone on the command line and try to "run" it. E.g. if you "touch ls some stuff" then * will expand to "ls some stuff" so it actually runs ls command. :-) Not practical, dangerous even.
